doctor went through three rewrites in one session.

v1: prescriptive. Checked for departure notes, root tree constraints,
tested-by coverage, doc drift. Told you what was wrong and what to fix.
Problem: assumed our workflow. A user with 5 notes on key decisions
would get a wall of false warnings.

v2: 'structural but descriptive.' Separated graph/kinds/edges/drift
sections. Still had doc-drift checking (does README mention all
commands?). Problem: doc drift is OUR concern for OUR repo. It
belongs in our test suite, not in the tool.

v3: white hat. Three numbers: notes (current/stale/orphaned),
edges (count), kinds (breakdown). No should, no missing, no drift.
Like git status — reports what IS, not what OUGHT TO BE.

The tension: every useful check is also an opinion. 'Decisions should
have tested-by edges' is useful for us but prescriptive for everyone.
The line we drew: doctor reports the state of the note graph itself.
Not the state of your project. Your project's standards go in your
notes (kind constraint, kind value), not in the tool's commands.

Aplumb inspired this — its doctor/gaps/coverage commands check
spec↔test↔code sync. But aplumb is deliberately opinionated (it has
a spec-driven development model). Mycelium is deliberately not. The
tool is the graph. The opinions are in the notes.
